AGI - Iran's President Ebrahim Raisi>, who died yesterday following the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-20/raisi-morto-accident- helicopter-26453916/"> helicopter crash/a> was one of the main candidates for the succession of the Ali Khamenei Supreme Guide". The latter, at 85 years old, has been committed to ensuring a succession that gives continuity to the Islamic Republic.
&nbsp;
The sudden death of Raisi is destined to have repercussions on plans for the after Khamenei. The Supreme Guide recently reiterated full support for Raisi and his government action - strongly criticized instead by the electorate who expressed himself with a record abstention in the last legislative in March - allowing the deceased president to expand his influence and place his men in the rooms of the power of the regime.
&nbsp;
To facilitate the possible rise of Raisi to the most important armchair of Iran were not only the clerical positions, but also a resume that before the presidency had seen him pass for the Imam Reza Foundation (as well as Khamenei before him) and the vice-presidentship of the Assembly of Experts, one of the most important institutions of the Islamic Republic born in 1979.
<h2> The son of Khamenei returns on track
The stage exit of such a figure inevitably ends with the scrambling of the cards in the fight against succession and relaunching some names, firstly that of the son of the Supreme Guide Khamenei, Mojtaba>. For years seen as the "grey eminence of the regime", its name has been circulating for years and arouses fears, based on the fact that the Islamic Republic could further tighten on opposition and population. Mojtaba, 53 years old, has always maintained a confidential profile, but he was able to move behind the scenes and increase his influence in the circle closer to his father.
&nbsp;
Figure close to the top of the Guardians of the Revolution, Mojtaba is also the number one of the Beit-e Rahbari, the office of the Supreme Guide. Beit is considered in Iran a shadow-institution of the Iranian institutional apparatus, called to assess the conformity of decisions made by political bodies to the principles that inspired the Iranian revolution and the will of the Supreme Guide.
&nbsp;
The action of the Beit takes shape in the shadows and the climb to the presidency by the son of Khamenei was the fruit of a paternal appointment. Circumstances, however, have created a boomerang effect: a population exasperated by corruption and suffering from a chronic economic crisis has manifested many times annoyance, if not hatred, for the rise in the power of Mojtaba Khamenei. A transversal insufficiency that does not favour the race of 'Aghazadeh', the 'son of the Lord', nicknamed to him by Iranian public opinion.&nbsp;
